## 10. Architectural Issues

### 10.1 Monolithic Files

**Description**

AI tends to put all requested functionality into a single large file rather than decomposing into modules.

**Bad Code**

```typescript
// api/routes.ts — 2000+ lines containing all routes, middleware, validation, DB queries
import express from "express";

const app = express();

// Auth middleware defined inline
app.use((req, res, next) => { /* 50 lines of auth logic */ });

// User routes with inline DB queries
app.get("/api/users", async (req, res) => { /* 80 lines */ });
app.post("/api/users", async (req, res) => { /* 100 lines */ });

// Order routes with inline DB queries
app.get("/api/orders", async (req, res) => { /* 90 lines */ });
app.post("/api/orders", async (req, res) => { /* 120 lines */ });

// ... 40 more route handlers
```

**Good Code**

```typescript
// app.ts
import express from "express";
import { authMiddleware } from "./middleware/auth";
import { userRouter } from "./routes/users";
import { orderRouter } from "./routes/orders";

const app = express();
app.use(authMiddleware);
app.use("/api/users", userRouter);
app.use("/api/orders", orderRouter);

export { app };

// routes/users.ts
import { Router } from "express";
import { createUser, getUsers } from "../services/userService";
import { CreateUserSchema } from "../schemas/user";

export const userRouter = Router();

userRouter.get("/", async (req, res) => {
  const users = await getUsers();
  res.json(users);
});

userRouter.post("/", async (req, res) => {
  const data = CreateUserSchema.parse(req.body);
  const user = await createUser(data);
  res.status(201).json(user);
});
```

**Why AI Makes This Mistake**

The model generates code sequentially within its output and does not naturally think in terms of file-system organisation. It also receives prompts in a single context and produces a single coherent response.

**Impact**

Monolithic files are difficult to navigate, review, test, and work on collaboratively. Merge conflicts increase, and build tools may not tree-shake effectively.

**Detection and Mitigation**

- Set file length limits in ESLint (`max-lines` rule, e.g., 300 lines).
- Organise by feature or layer (routes, services, repositories).
- When prompting AI, explicitly request separate files for separate concerns.

---

### 10.2 Excessive Comments

**Description**

AI adds comments to nearly every line, restating what the code already expresses clearly.

**Bad Code**

```typescript
// Import the express library
import express from "express";

// Create a new express application
const app = express();

// Define the port number
const PORT = 3000;

// Create a GET endpoint for the root path
app.get("/", (req, res) => {
  // Send a response with the text "Hello World"
  res.send("Hello World");
});

// Start the server and listen on the specified port
app.listen(PORT, () => {
  // Log a message when the server starts
  console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`);
});
```

**Good Code**

```typescript
import express from "express";

const app = express();
const PORT = process.env.PORT ?? 3000;

app.get("/", (_req, res) => {
  res.send("Hello World");
});

// Bind to 0.0.0.0 in containers to accept external connections
app.listen(PORT, "0.0.0.0", () => {
  console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`);
});
```

**Why AI Makes This Mistake**

AI is trained to be "helpful" and interprets this as being explanatory. Training data includes heavily commented tutorial code. The model errs on the side of over-explaining.

**Impact**

Comment noise makes code harder to scan, increases file size, and creates a maintenance burden (comments must be updated when code changes, but often are not).

**Detection and Mitigation**

- Comment _why_, not _what_. If the code is clear, no comment is needed.
- Remove AI-generated comments that restate the code during review.
- Focus comments on non-obvious business logic, workarounds, and architectural decisions.

---

### 10.3 Duplicated Logic

**Description**

AI duplicates logic across files instead of extracting shared utilities, especially when generating multiple similar handlers or components.

**Bad Code**

```typescript
// routes/users.ts
app.post("/api/users", async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const data = req.body;
    if (!data.email || !data.email.includes("@")) {
      return res.status(400).json({ error: "Invalid email" });
    }
    const user = await db.users.create({ data });
    res.json(user);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
    res.status(500).json({ error: "Internal server error" });
  }
});

// routes/invites.ts — same validation and error handling duplicated
app.post("/api/invites", async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const data = req.body;
    if (!data.email || !data.email.includes("@")) {
      return res.status(400).json({ error: "Invalid email" });
    }
    const invite = await db.invites.create({ data });
    res.json(invite);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
    res.status(500).json({ error: "Internal server error" });
  }
});
```

**Good Code**

```typescript
// middleware/validate.ts
import { z, ZodSchema } from "zod";
import { RequestHandler } from "express";

export function validate(schema: ZodSchema): RequestHandler {
  return (req, res, next) => {
    const result = schema.safeParse(req.body);
    if (!result.success) {
      return res.status(400).json({ errors: result.error.flatten() });
    }
    req.body = result.data;
    next();
  };
}

// middleware/errorHandler.ts
export const errorHandler: ErrorRequestHandler = (err, _req, res, _next) => {
  logger.error(err);
  res.status(500).json({ error: "Internal server error" });
};

// routes/users.ts
const CreateUserSchema = z.object({ email: z.string().email(), name: z.string() });

app.post("/api/users", validate(CreateUserSchema), async (req, res) => {
  const user = await db.users.create({ data: req.body });
  res.json(user);
});

// routes/invites.ts
const CreateInviteSchema = z.object({ email: z.string().email() });

app.post("/api/invites", validate(CreateInviteSchema), async (req, res) => {
  const invite = await db.invites.create({ data: req.body });
  res.json(invite);
});
```

**Why AI Makes This Mistake**

Each prompt or generation is somewhat independent. The model does not maintain a mental model of what utilities already exist in the codebase. It generates a self-contained solution each time.

**Impact**

Bug fixes must be applied in multiple places, inconsistencies creep in between duplicated implementations, and the codebase grows faster than necessary.

**Detection and Mitigation**

- Use code duplication detection tools (SonarQube, jscpd).
- Extract shared patterns into middleware, utility functions, or base classes.
- When prompting AI, provide existing utility code as context.

---

### 10.4 Missing Environment Validation

**Description**

AI accesses `process.env` directly without validation, leading to runtime errors when environment variables are missing or malformed.

**Bad Code**

```typescript
const dbUrl = process.env.DATABASE_URL; // string | undefined
const port = process.env.PORT; // string | undefined

// No validation — crashes at runtime if missing
const db = new PrismaClient({ datasources: { db: { url: dbUrl } } });
app.listen(port);
```

**Good Code**

```typescript
import { z } from "zod";

const envSchema = z.object({
  DATABASE_URL: z.string().url(),
  PORT: z.coerce.number().int().min(1).max(65535).default(3000),
  NODE_ENV: z.enum(["development", "production", "test"]).default("development"),
  API_KEY: z.string().min(1),
});

// Validate at startup — fail fast with a clear error
export const env = envSchema.parse(process.env);

const db = new PrismaClient({ datasources: { db: { url: env.DATABASE_URL } } });
app.listen(env.PORT);
```

**Why AI Makes This Mistake**

Direct `process.env` access is the norm in training data. Validation libraries for environment variables are less commonly shown. The model follows the path of least friction.

**Impact**

Missing or malformed environment variables cause cryptic runtime errors that may not surface until a specific code path is hit. This is especially dangerous in production deployments.

**Detection and Mitigation**

- Validate all environment variables at application startup using zod, envalid, or `t3-env`.
- Fail fast: if a required variable is missing, crash immediately with a clear error message.
- Never use `process.env` directly outside the validation module.

---

## Recommended Detection Toolchain

| Tool / Rule | Category | What It Catches |
|---|---|---|
| `"strict": true` in tsconfig.json | Type Safety | Implicit `any`, unchecked null, unknown catch variables |
| `"noUncheckedIndexedAccess": true` | Runtime Errors | Unsafe array/object index access |
| `@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any` | Type Safety | Explicit `any` annotations |
| `@typescript-eslint/no-floating-promises` | Async | Missing `await` on promises |
| `@typescript-eslint/no-misused-promises` | Async | Promises in boolean contexts, void callbacks |
| `@typescript-eslint/no-unsafe-member-access` | Type Safety | Property access on `any`/`unknown` typed values |
| `@typescript-eslint/consistent-type-assertions` | Type Safety | Unsafe `as` casts |
| `eslint-plugin-security` | Security | `eval()`, `exec()`, prototype pollution patterns |
| `eslint-plugin-react-hooks` (exhaustive-deps) | React | Missing/incorrect useEffect dependencies |
| `eslint-plugin-react` | React/Security | `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`, deprecated APIs |
| `no-empty` (ESLint core) | Error Handling | Empty catch blocks |
| `max-lines` (ESLint core) | Architecture | Monolithic files |
| `npm audit` | Dependencies | Known vulnerabilities in installed packages |
| [Socket.dev](https://socket.dev) | Dependencies | Malicious/typosquatted packages, supply-chain attacks |
| [Snyk](https://snyk.io) | Security / Dependencies | Vulnerabilities in code and dependencies |
| [SonarQube](https://www.sonarqube.org) | All | Code smells, bugs, security hotspots, duplication |
| `gitleaks` / `trufflehog` | Security | Hardcoded secrets in source code |
| `webpack-bundle-analyzer` | Performance | Oversized bundles from unnecessary dependencies |

